<br /><br />6.Keep your feet off the seats or pay for my dry-cleaning;
<br /><br />7.The discussion you’re having with your girlfriend doesn’t interest us – shut up;
<br /><br />8.When you manoeuvre into the seat nest to me, acknowledge my existence;
<br /><br />9.The book, telephone, paper or magazine doesn’t reserve a seat – it’s public transport, remember;
<br /><br />10.That gratuitous display of affection for your partner is boorish  - get a room;
<br /><br />11.When you get into a carriage keep moving, don’t stop. There are people behind you trying to get on;
<br /><br />12.You might get the same seat each day – until someone else sits in it. Don’t get angry, get over it;
<br /><br />13.Don’t run the length of the platform to get on the train. There are doors from carriage to carriage on the inside. The front doesn’t get to the station much quicker;
<br /><br />14.You pay for one seat, so don’t spread your stuff all over the seats next to you;
<br /><br />15.I’m sitting down and you’re standing up. When you turn around abruptly, please be careful the bag you’ve got over your shoulder doesn’t take my head off;
<br /><br />16.Civilised humans wear pants, a shirt and some sort of footwear when outside. None of these are optional on public transport. See rule 6.

